Every Angular developer has stared at a sprawling NgRx codebase and thought, вЂњDo I really need an Action, Reducer, Effect, and Selector just to toggle a dropdown or manage a multi-step form?вЂќ
For years, we accepted the boilerplate because the predictable, event-driven architecture of NgRx kept our enterprise applications from collapsing into chaos. But when the Angular team introduced Signals, the community started asking a dangerous question: Should we abandon traditional NgRx entirely?
The answer is a resounding no.
The new gold standard in modern Angular architecture isnвЂ™t about choosing between global event-driven state and local reactive state. ItвЂ™s about seamlessly combining them. Here is how to build a scalable, developer-friendly architecture using traditional NgRx for global orchestration and the new NgRx SignalStore for highly reactive, local feature state.
The Core Philosophy: Two Brains are Better Than One
To understand this architecture, you have to stop looking at state as a single monolith. Your application actually has two different вЂњnervous systems,вЂќ and they need different tools.

вЂў The Global Nervous System (Traditional NgRx)
This is your appвЂ™s central hub. It is event-driven, declarative, and shared. Components here donвЂ™t mutate state; they shout into the void that something happened (e.g., вЃ [Auth] User Logged InвЃ ), and the global store decides how to react.
What lives here?
User authentication and permissions.
Application-wide settings (dark mode, language preferences).
Shared entity caches used across completely unrelated features.
Cross-cutting events (handling 401 Unauthorized API responses via Effects).
2. The Local Brain (NgRx SignalStore)
This is the state tied directly to a specific feature or route. It is method-based, imperative, and highly reactive. It lives and dies with the component or route it serves.
What lives here?
The data currently loaded in a specific data grid or dashboard.
Pagination, sorting, and filtering parameters for a single page.
Complex, multi-step form state.
Direct API orchestrations for a localized feature.
The Blueprint: Folder Structure
When you mix paradigms, your boundaries must be visually obvious the second a developer opens the repository. We lean heavily into Domain-Driven Design (DDD) to keep the global state pure and the feature states isolated.
src/app/
в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ core/ # рџЊЌ THE GLOBAL ZONE (Loaded on startup)
в”‚ в”њв”Ђв”Ђ services/
в”‚ в””в”Ђв”Ђ state/ # Traditional NgRx
в”‚ в”њв”Ђв”Ђ app.state.ts
в”‚ в”њв”Ђв”Ђ auth/
в”‚ в”‚ в”њв”Ђв”Ђ auth.actions.ts
в”‚ в”‚ в”њв”Ђв”Ђ auth.effects.ts
в”‚ в”‚ в””в”Ђв”Ђ auth.reducer.ts
в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ shared/ # рџ§± REUSABLE UI (Dumb components only)
в”‚ в””в”Ђв”Ђ components/
в”‚ в””в”Ђв”Ђ ui-button/ # No state injected here!
в”‚
в””в”Ђв”Ђ features/ # рџ§© THE FEATURE ZONE (Lazy-loaded)
в”‚
в””в”Ђв”Ђ profile/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ components/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ services/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ profile.routes.ts
