The Golden Rule: Features are completely selfish. The вЃ profileвЃ  feature is never allowed to import a SignalStore from the вЃ ordersвЃ  feature. If they need to communicate, the feature must dispatch a global action.
Building the Bridge: How They Talk
The true power of this architecture is how easily these two systems interact. Because both are built for the modern Angular ecosystem, your local SignalStore can inject the global вЃ StoreвЃ  to read global context and dispatch global events.
LetвЂ™s look at a practical example. Imagine a вЃ ProfileStoreвЃ  (our local SignalStore) that needs to update a userвЂ™s avatar. It needs the вЃ userIdвЃ  from the Global Store to make the API call, and once successful, it needs to dispatch a global action so the appвЂ™s top navigation bar updates the userвЂ™s picture.
import { inject } from '@angular/core';
import { Store } from '@ngrx/store';
import { signalStore, withState, withMethods, patchState, withComputed } from '@ngrx/signals';
import { rxMethod } from '@ngrx/signals/rxjs-interop';
import { pipe, switchMap, tap } from 'rxjs';// 1. Import Global State selectors and actions
import { selectUserId } from '../../core/state/auth/auth.selectors';
import { AuthActions } from '../../core/state/auth/auth.actions';
import { ProfileApiService } from '../services/profile-api.service';
interface ProfileState {
isUploading: boolean;
uploadError: string | null;
}
const initialState: ProfileState = {
isUploading: false,
uploadError: null,
};
export const ProfileStore = signalStore(
withState(initialState),
// 2. Read from the Global Store using computed signals
withComputed((_, globalStore = inject(Store)) => ({
currentUserId: globalStore.selectSignal(selectUserId)
})),
withMethods((
store,
api = inject(ProfileApiService),
globalStore = inject(Store) // Inject the global NgRx Store
) => ({
// 3. Imperative method called directly by the UI component
updateAvatar: rxMethod<File>(
pipe(
tap(() => patchState(store, { isUploading: true, uploadError: null })),
switchMap((file) => {
// Use the computed signal derived from global state
const userId = store.currentUserId();
return api.uploadAvatar(userId, file).pipe(
tap({
next: (response) => {
patchState(store, { isUploading: false });
// 4. Dispatch to the Global Store so the rest of the app reacts!
globalStore.dispatch(AuthActions.avatarUpdated({ newUrl: response.url }));
},
error: (err) => {
patchState(store, { isUploading: false, uploadError: err.message });
}
})
);
})
)
)
}))
);
Why this is a game-changer:

вЂў Zero Global Clutter: The global store doesnвЂ™t need to know about вЃ isUploadingвЃ  or вЃ uploadErrorвЃ . That transient UI state is handled perfectly by the local SignalStore.

вЂў 2. Strict Traceability: The moment the avatar actually changes, a formal action (вЃ [Auth] Avatar UpdatedвЃ ) is dispatched globally, allowing the Redux DevTools to track the data flow across the app.

вЂў 3. Incredible DX: The component developer just calls вЃ profileStore.updateAvatar(file)вЃ . They donвЂ™t have to wire up complex effects or track loading selectors.

вЂў The Takeaway

вЂў By marrying traditional NgRx with the new SignalStore, you get the best of both worlds. You retain the strict, event-driven traceability required to keep an enterprise app stable, while recovering the rapid, imperative developer experience that makes building individual features actually fun again.

вЂў Stop fighting the boilerplate, and start putting your state where it actually belongs.
